To top it all off I'm getting in 'trouble' for supposed plagiarism on a piece of artwork I handed in an art class. Now, it's unfortunate I can't show you the piece due to the fact that my scanner is in the 'shop' being fixed, but maybe I can describe what my piece looks like.<br>
Ok, ignoring the rest of the subject matter which includes some rough clouds and some guys in roman-esque armor in the foreground, I have a large demon that accumulates half my drawing. This demon has like a... cow's head with the horns turned downward and big pointy teeth. Pretty stereo-typical, however not copied.<br>
I get dragged out of the room today and shown a bunch of internet print-outs of what looks to be some Todd Mcfarlane Spawn art. I get scolded by being accused of copying this artist. Bah! I've never bought one his comcis in my entire life.<br>
My art teacher starts talking about violating copy-right and whatnot, so I get smart and start in a very patronizing tone on how Todd Mcfarlane must have invented the concept of heaven and hell, because obviously he must 'own' the copyright to demons and somsuch.<br>
I even related ol' Dante's Inferno novel where the illustrated edition contains very old romantic era paintings of the creatures of heaven and hell. Now, instead of getting accused of copying Mcfarlane, I am now copying some paintings as old as the romantic era (hundreds of years ago)<br>
What do I do? Drawing a demon with horns, wings, and pointy teeth is well... definitely not that orginal. But I didn't 'copy' an artist.<br>
Do any of you bible experts know of any sort of passage where it explains the devil and his followers being deformed somehow into the whole 'horns and sharp teeth' aspect we've all come to know.?<br>
Now, the vice principal is involved. I don't want to have something like that on my perminant record when I go to apply to art school. It's bad enough my art teacher won't even keep my piece up on the wall because she doesn't want to promote 'copying'. Screw that. I drew it myself with only a plastacine cow skull for reference.<br>
I don't understand how someone in the same class can alter a Mona Lisa and get called an artist, while I use a concept that's as old as painting itself and get accused of plagiarising.<br>
What a load of bull @#$$#!<br>
